.CD "fgrep \(en fixed grep"
.SX "fgrep\fR [\fB\(encfhlnsv\fR]\fR [\fIstring_file\fR] [\fIstring\fR] [\fIfile\fR] ..."
.FL "\(enc" "Count matching lines and only print count, not the lines"
.FL "\(enf" "Take strings from file named in following argument"
.FL "\(enh" "Omit file headers from printout"
.FL "\(enl" "List file names once only"
.FL "\(enn" "Each line is preceded by its line number"
.FL "\(ens" "Status only, no output"
.FL "\(env" "Print only lines not matching"
.EX "fgrep % prog.c" "Print lines containing % sign"
.EX "fgrep \(enf pattern prog.c" "Take strings from \fIpattern\fR"
.PP
\fIFgrep\fR is essentially the same as grep, except that it only searches
for lines containing literal strings (no wildcard characters).  The pattern
may consist of several lines with one string to search on each line.



